stylometry: The logical upper limit is the maximum number able to be produced, or the minimum number that has to be produced, depending on the problem you are approaching. Logical upper limits are used in place of IF statements when running Solver because of the fact that Solver does not necessarily "behave" with an IF statement in them. A logical upper limit statement however can go into Solver with no issues becasue of the way it looks at the max or min of a set of data, providing the same result as an IF statement.
